V16: Questions were asked on a computer screen and then a word was said in headphones that the subject wore. Upon hearing the word, while still looking at the screen, the subject was supposed to accurately answer the question with yes/up or no/down.
V17: I guess I moved closer to engage more with the screen and I know I looked down when there was a pattern even though I know that was discouraged. I don't know if it worked. I know I was pretty tired so by moving closer I felt more engaged. I also thought about what possible answers could be where permitted. This worked some of the time.
V18: Yes, I think they slowed down my performance. I definitely think that they were distracting and another sensory/other stimuli I had to block in order to remember the question and think about the correct answer.
V19: I think they are going to look at question accuracy and speed and distract-ability. Mostly, I think they are studying the relationship between distract-ability with moving visuals with respect to written and auditory learning

V16: I saw a question on the screen then heard the name of an object. I would press the up arrow if the answer to the question was yes, and pressed the down arrow if the answer to the question was no.
V17: Sometimes I would guess what object I expected to hear. In some instances this helped me respond more quickly, but in some cases it was confusing and slowed my reaction time.
V18: Yes, but I couldn't tell if this had any effect on my performance.
V19: I think they hope to find the time it takes for the brain to make connections between objects and certain traits these objects possess.

V16: A question about an object that I had to read showed up on the computer screen and then I heard a word. I had to then answer the question yes or no based on the object I heard.
V17: Sometimes when I thought the question was referring to one object in particular (ex: does it have a long neck I would think the yes answer was giraffe) so as soon as I did not hear the word I thought they were getting at, I would click no. I think it worked in most cases but in some I answered too quickly and then answered the question wrong.
V18: Yes, I think I answered the questions faster when the flashing patterns were present because they helped me focus.
V19: That our brains respond faster to certain words than others.
